% Automatisch generiert — Thema: School Uniforms
% arg/1 Fakten
arg(pro82).  % [pro] Uniforms help troubled students feel that troubled students have the support of a community.
arg(pro15).  % [pro] When students are dressed alike, students are safer.
arg(pro4).  % [pro] Students dressed in uniform are better perceived by teachers and peers.
arg(pro95).  % [pro] Former US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton, when she was a 2008 US presidential candidate, advocated school uniforms as a way to help students focus on learning, saying: “Take clothing choices off the table and put the focus on school, not on what students are wearing.”
arg(pro36).  % [pro] Uniforms provide less distraction.
arg(pro36b).  % [pro] Uniforms provide less drama.
arg(pro36c).  % [pro] Uniforms provide more focus on learning.
arg(pro32).  % [pro] It is very important that girls do not have to give in to these sorts of pressures.
arg(pro32b).  % [pro] Girls actually welcome wearing a uniform.
arg(pro29).  % [pro] If someone were to come into a building, the intruder could easily be recognized.
arg(con36).  % [con] Nothing says 'the issue is not just about you' more than an ugly uniform.
arg(con27).  % [con] The school's uniform policy broke the guarantee of a free public education.
arg(con27b).  % [con] The school's uniform policy violated children's right to freedom of expression.
arg(con27c).  % [con] The parents were required to pay $641 for their children's uniforms in August 2007.
arg(con140).  % [con] Most public schools with uniform policies are located in poor neighborhoods.
arg(con140b).  % [con] Uniform policies emphasize the class distinctions that uniforms were supposed to eliminate.
arg(con23).  % [con] The paper titled “Public School Uniforms: Effect on Perceptions of Gang Presence, School Climate, and Student Self-Perceptions” shows that students who are not required to wear school uniforms demonstrated higher self-perception scores.
arg(con109).  % [con] However, serious discipline and academic issues are unlikely to be solved by nostalgically resurrecting the blazer or draconian decrees issued from the headmaster's study regarding skirt length.
arg(con9).  % [con] A student's transition towards adulthood can be hindered by uniforms.
arg(con8).  % [con] There are limited choices for males.
arg(con8b).  % [con] There are limited choices for females.

% att/2 Fakten  (Dung 1995 — binär; Typ/conf aus LLM-Kandidaten als Kommentar)
att(con36, pro82).  % [undermining] conf=70 — The claim that ugly uniforms highlight individual issues attacks the premise that uniforms foster community support for troubled students.
att(con140b, pro82).  % [undermining] conf=70 — Con argues uniforms emphasize class distinctions, challenging the premise that they foster community support for troubled students.
att(con23, pro82).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — Con presents evidence that non‑uniform students have higher self‑perception, directly contradicting the pro claim that uniforms help troubled students feel supported.
att(con140, pro15).  % [undercutting] conf=70 — Shows that uniform policies are concentrated in poor neighborhoods, suggesting safety may be due to other factors, not the uniforms themselves.
att(con140b, pro4).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — Emphasizing class distinctions opposes the claim that uniforms improve perception.
att(con23, pro4).  % [rebuttal] conf=85 — Higher self‑perception without uniforms contradicts the claim that uniforms lead to better perception.
att(con36, pro4).  % [undermining] conf=85 — Con36 argues uniforms are ugly, challenging the premise that uniforms lead to better perception by teachers and peers.
att(con36, pro95).  % [undermining] conf=60 — The claim that ugly uniforms highlight self‑interest challenges the premise that uniforms improve focus.
att(con27, pro95).  % [undermining] conf=70 — Arguing that uniform policies break the guarantee of free public education attacks the legitimacy of the policy advocated.
att(con27b, pro95).  % [undermining] conf=80 — Stating that uniforms violate children's freedom of expression directly attacks the premise that such policies are acceptable.
att(con140b, pro95).  % [undermining] conf=70 — Saying uniforms emphasize class distinctions contradicts the implied premise that they create a neutral learning environment.
att(con23, pro95).  % [undercutting] conf=75 — Empirical evidence that non‑uniformed students have higher self‑perception undermines the inference that uniforms improve learning outcomes.
att(con109, pro95).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — Con claims uniforms won’t solve discipline or academic problems, directly contradicting Pro’s claim that they help focus on learning
att(con36, pro36).  % [undermining] conf=65 — Con attacks the premise that uniforms are neutral by claiming an ugly uniform emphasizes self‑centeredness, weakening Pro’s claim of reduced distraction
att(con140b, pro36).  % [undermining] conf=85 — Argues uniforms emphasize class distinctions, challenging the premise that they reduce distraction
att(con36, pro36b).  % [undermining] conf=70 — The con argument attacks the premise that uniforms reduce drama by suggesting an ugly uniform creates personal focus and potential drama.
att(con140b, pro36b).  % [undermining] conf=65 — It argues that uniforms emphasize class distinctions, which could increase drama, undermining the premise that they reduce drama.
att(con8, pro36b).  % [undermining] conf=70 — Limited choices for males challenges the premise that uniforms reduce drama by suggesting reduced choice may cause resentment.
att(con8b, pro36b).  % [undermining] conf=70 — Limited choices for females questions the premise that uniforms lower drama, implying restricted options could increase tension.
att(con27c, pro36c).  % [undermining] conf=70 — The high cost of uniforms challenges the premise that uniforms are an overall net benefit for student learning.
att(con140b, pro36c).  % [undermining] conf=80 — con140b claims uniforms highlight class differences, challenging the premise that they reduce distractions and improve focus.
att(con23, pro36c).  % [undermining] conf=70 — con23 presents evidence that non‑uniform students have higher self‑perception, questioning the premise that uniforms boost learning focus.
att(con109, pro36c).  % [rebuttal] conf=95 — con109 states uniforms are unlikely to solve academic issues, directly contradicting pro36c’s claim that they increase learning focus.
att(con36, pro32b).  % [undermining] conf=85 — The claim that uniforms are ugly attacks the premise that girls would welcome wearing them.
att(pro82, con23).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — [symmetric rebuttal] Con presents evidence that non‑uniform students have higher self‑perception, directly contradicting the pro claim that uniforms help troubled students feel supported.
att(pro4, con140b).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — [symmetric rebuttal] Emphasizing class distinctions opposes the claim that uniforms improve perception.
att(pro4, con23).  % [rebuttal] conf=85 — [symmetric rebuttal] Higher self‑perception without uniforms contradicts the claim that uniforms lead to better perception.
att(pro95, con109).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — [symmetric rebuttal] Con claims uniforms won’t solve discipline or academic problems, directly contradicting Pro’s claim that they help focus on learning
